Date: 25 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease information, 24 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_35.HTM#Sec3>

Bovine spongiform encephalopathy in Japan
------------------------------------------
(Date of previous case of bovine spongiform encephalopathy in Japan
reported to the OIE: August 2002).
Information received on 21 Jan 2003 from Dr Toshikazu Ijichi, director of
Animal Health Division, Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries,
Tokyo: report date: 21 Jan 2003.
One outbreak, laboratory confirmed on 20 Jan 2003, Naga gun, Wakayama
Prefecture. Affected population: a Holstein cow aged 6 years and 11 months,
born in Hokkaido Prefecture and then transferred to a dairy farm in
Wakayama Prefecture, which was slaughtered at the abattoir on 17 Jan 2003.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species / susceptible /cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
bov / ... / 1 / 0 / ... / 1
Diagnosis:
- The brain sample from the cow tested positive to the ELISA-based BSE
screening test required by the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare for
all cattle slaughtered at abattoirs since 18 Oct 2001 (Wakayama City Public
Health Center, Meat Inspection Office (Wakayama city, Wakayama Prefecture)).
- The brain sample was sent to the National Institute of Infectious Disease
(Shinjuku-ku, Tokyo) for confirmation and was subjected to western blot
analysis and immunohistochemical examination, with a positive result on 20
Jan 2003.
Source of agent / origin of infection: under investigation.
Control measures:
- The dairy farm in Wakayama Prefecture where the affected animal was kept
and the dairy farm in Hokkaido Prefecture where it was born have been
placed under movement control by Kihoku Livestock Hygiene Service Center
and Kushiro Livestock Hygiene Service Center, respectively.
- Identification of all animals that were kept with the infected cow.
- Epidemiological investigation of the feed used on the farm, as a possible
source of infection.
Note from the OIE Central Bureau: As from now, any further cases of BSE in
Japan will no longer be notified in Disease Information but will
immediately be incorporated into the table on the number of reported cases
of BSE worldwide (excluding the United Kingdom).
