[6]
Date: 07 Feb 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EU Food Safety - scientific committees opinions [edited]
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/fs/sc/ssc/out311_en.pdf>

SSC opinions on waste-disposal systems
--------------------------------------
The Scientific Steering Committee of the EU has adopted, during its meeting
on 16-17 Jan 2003, the following opinions on BSE risk reduction by means of
3 waste disposal systems. These are their respective summaries:
1. The use of small incinerators for BSE risk reduction.
Small incinerators are widely used to meet the needs of local communities.
These incinerators vary greatly in their design, nature of use, performance
characteristics, and the quality of their management. As a consequence of
this variability, there are many uncertainties in identifying risks posed
by small incinerators that are used to treat SRM [specified risk material],
and each type should eventually receive its own assessment. Also, general
operating and control criteria should be established for safe incineration,
as it has been done for large incinerators.
2. Open burning of potentially transmissible spongiform encephalopathy
infected animal materials.
(1) "Burning" covers a wide variety of combustion conditions. This opinion
is concerned with the process of open burning -- for example, bonfires.
(2) There are serious concerns regarding the use of open burning for the
destruction of pathogen-contaminated animal waste, particularly for waste
which may be contaminated with relatively heat-stable pathogens. Issues
include: the potentially very high variability of the pathogen
inactivation, the nature of the gaseous and particulate emissions, and the
risks from the residual ash.
(3) The SSC recommends that open burning is considered for pathogen
destruction only under exceptional circumstances following a specific risk
assessment. In the case of animal waste possibly contaminated with BSE/TSE
in view of the uncertainty of the risk, open burning should be considered a
risk. Suitable monitoring methods for TSE contamination of both air and ash
are needed. Protocols for safe burning in emergency situations need to be
established.
3.The use of burial for dealing with animal carcasses and other animal
materials that might contain BSE/TSE.
(1) The term "burial" includes a diversity of disposal conditions. Although
burial is widely used for disposal of waste, the degradation process
essential for BSE/TSE infectivity reduction is very difficult to control.
The extent to which such an infectivity reduction can occur as a
consequence of burial is poorly characterised. It would appear to be a slow
process in various circumstances.
(2) A number of concerns have been identified including potential for
groundwater contamination, dispersal/transmission by birds/animals/insects,
and accidental uncovering by man.
(3) In the absence of any new data, the SSC confirms its previous opinion
that for animal material which could possibly be contaminated with BSE/TSE,
burial poses a risk except under highly controlled conditions (for example,
controlled landfill).
