Date: Mon 20 Jan 2003
From: Premed-mail<premed@promed mail.or>
Source: Press release, Ministry of Agriculture & Rural Development, 19 Jan
2003 [translated from Hebrew, edited]
<http://www.moag.gov.il/>

Israel's plan to prevent mad cow disease in humans
--------------------------------------------------
The Israeli government has approved the proposal of the minister of
agriculture, Zippi Livni, to extend the programme for the prevention of mad
cow disease in humans. The allocated annual budget is 17.6 million NIS [3.7
million US dollars], to be provided by 4 ministries: Agriculture (4.8),
Finance (4.8), Health (4.0), and Environment (4.0).
The programme includes 3 main components:
1. Continued brain testing of cattle older than 30 months, prior to their
release for human consumption.
2. Destruction of selected organs of cattle older than 15 months. The
relevant organs are the skull (excluding tongue and head meat), the spinal
cord, and the intestines. These organs are regarded as risky, since they
may contain the disease causative agent, the prion.
3. Intensified control, inspection, and law enforcement upon cattle
movements and their slaughter. This relates mainly to the prevention of
illegal slaughter without veterinary inspection.
The Veterinary Services in the Ministry of Agriculture have informed that
since the programme was initially put into operation in July 2002, more
than 5000 cows have been examined at the Veterinary Institute, Beit-Dagan,
all found healthy.
--
ProMED-mail
<premed@promed mail.or>
[The actual number of animals tested since 2002 within the Israeli BSE
programme exceeds 11 000. This includes 53 clinically suspected, 896 fallen
stock, and 10 238 "healthy", over 30 months old slaughtered cattle. The
first and only positive case was a 10 year old clinically suspected cow,
diagnosed on 29 May 2002. See Weekly BSE report, 30 Jan to 5 Feb 2003:
<http://agri3.huji.ac.il/~yakobson/bse/bse_test.htm> - Mod.AS]
